## Visual design of the clock face, when reproduced outside the screen

The MIT-licensed source code renders the clock on screens — web, mobile,
desktop. That use is unrestricted, including embedding the app inside other
software (tablet learning apps, websites, educational platforms). What is
separately reserved is the *visual design itself* when lifted out of the
running app and into another medium, including:

- Physical products: clocks, watches, toys, educational materials, stationery
- Merchandise: apparel, stickers, prints, accessories, plush goods
- Print publications, broadcast media, or any other non-software reproduction
- AI-generated derivatives intended for any of the above

This reservation covers, but is not limited to:

- The color-placement scheme: in all palettes except "そらのいろ"
  (sky colors) and "ものとーん" (monotone), contrasting colors are
  deliberately arranged in a non-adjacent manner around the dial,
  serving as visual anchors and reference lines for early learners
  (as opposed to rainbow-order, hue-wheel-order, or sequential
  gradient arrangements common in other educational clocks)

- The named color palette set and its specific color values,
  including the Japanese and English names of each palette:
    - "くっきりいろ" / crisp colors
    - "あおきみどり" / sky sun grass
    - "さんげんしょく" / 3 primaries
    - "いろのわ" / color wheel
    - "みんなのいろ" / universal
    - "そらのいろ" / sky colors
    - "ものとーん" / monotone
  The pedagogical rationale behind each palette is documented
  separately by the author.
- The AM/PM dual-face composition and layout
- The "kasaneru" (重ねる) overlap behavior and its visual expression
- The sun-and-moon sky illustration
- The stage-progression dial layouts
  (Badge × Simple / Slices × Detailed / Slices × Simple)

